Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.71,0:00:43.63,Default,,0,0,30,,Wit is your weapon{honestly no clue what is megurase here, deepl says "rack one's brain"}\NRemember to use your head{智恵をめぐらせ 頭を使え}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.63,0:00:51.25,Default,,0,0,30,,Repress your anguish, \NIf you are a man{悩み抜け抜け 男なら}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.25,0:00:59.25,Default,,0,0,30,,One decision is enough \NTo make others cry or laugh{泣くも笑うも 決断ひとつ}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.25,0:01:06.99,Default,,0,0,30,,If you win, don't hold your head high, \NIf you lose, don't cry{勝っておごるな 敗れて泣くな}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.99,0:01:14.55,Default,,0,0,30,,Men, don't you ever let others see your tears{男 涙は見せぬもの}
Comment: 0,0:01:35.21,0:01:35.25,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.72,0:01:45.27,Default,,0,0,0,,December 2, 1941, Sanya Harbor, Hainan Island. {On December 4, 1941, Vice Admiral Jisaburo Ozawa , commander of the Magai unit, who confirmed the sortie of all fleets of the operation in Sanya, finally led the main unit of the Magura unit and sortied from there . [ 20] By 8:00 a.m., the Murray Capture Fleet had finished forming patrol form}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.69,0:01:55.54,Default,,0,0,0,,With the heavy cruiser Chokai as its flagship, \Na considerable escort fleet quietly rallied. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_cruiser_Ch%C5%8Dkai}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.54,0:01:59.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Led by Lieutenant General Tomoyuki Yamashita, \Nthe 25th army prepared to embark.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.87,0:02:04.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Carrying them was the mobile transport fleet{/convoy}, \Ncomposed of a dozen ships, including Ryujo Maru. {Shinshū Maru (神州丸 or 神洲丸) was a ship of the Japanese Imperial Army during World War II. She was the world's first landing craft carrier ship to be designed as such, and a pioneer of modern-day amphibious assault ships.[1] During some of her operations, she was known to have used at least four cover names, R1, GL, MT, and Ryujo Maru.}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.29,0:02:14.29,Sign,,0,0,0,,{This is Tomoyuki Yamashita himself}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.70,0:02:16.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Excuse me.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.97,0:02:26.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, we just received \Nan emergency telegram addressed for you
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.10,0:02:28.85,Default,,0,0,0,,from the Commander-in-Chief \Nof the Southern Expeditionary Army.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.10,0:02:33.73,Default,,0,0,0,,I will read. Sender: \NSouthern Expeditionary Army Commander-in-Chief.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.73,0:02:38.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Recipient: 25th Army Commander. \N"The sun rises in{/day of the sunrise is} Yamagata." {In Continental Order No. 569 of the Malayan Landing Operation, "Hinode(sunrise)" is the date of the operation, and "Yamagata" is a slang word for the initials of the 8th. 1st = Hiroshima, 2nd = Fukuoka, 3rd = Miyazaki, 4th = Yokohama, 5th = Kokura, 6th = Muroran, 7th = Nagoya, 8th = Yamagata, 9th = Kurume, 10th = Tokyo It was.}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.96,0:02:42.12,Default,,0,0,0,,"The sun rises at Yamagata."
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.33,0:02:53.32,Default,,0,0,0,,So then, the war starts on December 8th. {outbreak of war; starting a war}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.51,0:03:01.03,Default,,0,0,0,,On December 8th, war was declared\Nand the Japanese Navy
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.03,0:03:05.04,Default,,0,0,0,,had dealt a surprise blow to the American fleet, \Nstationed at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.04,0:03:08.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, the infantry \Nwould also be dispatched on the mission
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.56,0:03:13.36,Default,,0,0,0,,of roaming the Malay Peninsula to take the \NPride of the British Empire, the great fortress of Singapore. {running through (north-south); cutting across; travelling across​}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:13.56,0:03:21.36,Sign,,0,0,300,,{\fade(300,00)\c&HC3C9C5&\bord0\blur1\b1}Episode 4: \N {\fs90} Blitzkrieg on Malay Peninsula {tosshin is rather "rush; dash; charge"}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.50,0:03:19.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Confronting two major powers at once: \NAmerica and Britain, Japan had planned
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.24,0:03:23.12,Default,,0,0,0,,to engage the Pacific war with a decisive{/dramatic/extreme} move, \Nbound to enter the annals of history.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.53,0:03:32.75,Default,,0,0,0,,In accordance with the Southern strategy, \Nthe units 5 and 18 formed a special corps, the 25th army. {I hope he means this} {it's important that both the units 5 and 18 retained their structure within the 25 army - they weren't disbanded, it'll be mentioned again later}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.75,0:03:38.06,Default,,0,0,0,,It was put under the command of lieutenant general Yamashita, honorably cited on the battlefield.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.38,0:03:45.57,Default,,0,0,0,,The capture of Singapore would become a major operation, \Nof immeasurable importance for the Japanese Army. {relative importance; weight}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.93,0:03:52.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Singapore, also known as “Gibraltar of the East" \Nis in fact a big impregnable{難攻不落} fortress.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.31,0:03:57.94,Default,,0,0,0,,A siege from the sea{/from sea} was deemed \Ntoo costly on our forces and therefore prejudicial.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.94,0:04:02.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead, we will approach Singapore from inland,\Nwhere it's more lightly defended.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.24,0:04:08.13,Default,,0,0,0,,In order to deceive the enemy, we will pretend to head \Nfor Thailand, only to go off course abruptly. {/our land army, ... with a sudden/all at once change of course; changing direction}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.13,0:04:13.02,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll disembark at 3 points simultaneously - Singora, Pattani, and Kota Bharu, advancing in two groups.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.28,0:04:22.13,Default,,0,0,0,,However, this strategy has \N3 issues that might complicate matters. {/3 difficult problems}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.26,0:04:28.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Firstly, our planned route has \Nover 250 bridges towards our destination.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:28.11,0:04:31.06,Default,,0,0,0,,If the enemy sabotage them, \Nour advance will be hampered. {/slowed down}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.56,0:04:34.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Secondly, the enemy's troops amount to about 80,000.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.69,0:04:38.42,Default,,0,0,0,,In comparison, our forces \Ncome to no more than 20,000.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.42,0:04:43.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, the third problem is that it has to be captured \Nby March 10th, the Army Memorial Day.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.49,0:04:48.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Through conventional warfare, we won't capture it, \Neven after half a year! We must sweep it!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.02,0:04:50.74,Default,,0,0,0,,As soon as we land, we overrun them, \Nwithout half-measure.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.74,0:04:53.48,Default,,0,0,0,,The forward{/attacking} units \Nhave to cut through the enemy's lines! {/just penetrate right in the middle of the enemy}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.48,0:04:57.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't even look back! Just let the vanilla units \Ndeal with the bulk of the enemy! {/following units}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.21,0:05:00.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Charge. Charge! {/rush}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.25,0:05:05.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Aim for Singapore straight on \Nin a lightning-fast charge!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.59,0:05:11.68,Default,,0,0,0,,On the morning of December 3rd, \Nthe fleet escorting the 25th Army {fleet (fishing, naval, etc.); convoy; group of ships}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.68,0:05:14.88,Default,,0,0,0,,departed for the northern coast \Nof the Malay Peninsula.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.48,0:05:25.67,Default,,0,0,0,,On December 7th, the fleet went past the southern tip \Nof French Indochina, and instead of turning north,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.67,0:05:29.07,Default,,0,0,0,,it{/en route} went off course, \Ntowards the northern cost of Malay Peninsula -
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.07,0:05:33.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Singora, Pattani, and Kota Bharu\N being the 3 starting points of a scattered assault.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.21,0:05:44.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Singapore is considered to be the gateway to the Indian Ocean.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.67,0:05:48.66,Default,,0,0,0,,A cornerstone to anyone \Naiming to be the master of the Strait of Malacca.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.66,0:05:54.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Capturing it was the key to the success of the entire Southern Operation. Moreover, it was a critical priority.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.30,0:06:02.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Prepare to disembark!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.61,0:06:51.58,Default,,0,0,0,,December 8th. Led personally by commander Yamashita, \Nthe special 25th front line unit{/vanguard army} landed in Singora.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.51,0:07:08.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Hold it! {no clue}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.72,0:07:11.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Commander, you can jump now!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.80,0:07:13.41,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.06,0:07:20.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't let commander down!{guess} Hurry!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.50,0:07:44.89,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army thus succeeded \Nto land unopposed in Singora, {lit: flawless disembarkment was a success - I don't know how it could be flawed if singora was by then in thailand, still a neutral country that gave them the basing rights so thinking maybe replace it with "Thai Singora" to mark that it wasn't supposed to have the enemy on site}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.89,0:07:46.84,Default,,0,0,0,,and headed straight for Singapore.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.84,0:07:50.13,Default,,0,0,0,,The blitzkrieg through Malay Peninsula had begun. {lit is "rush; dash; charge maneuver/operation"}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.31,0:08:13.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, the landing party in Kota Bharu \Nmet a fierce resistance from British defenders on the beach. {lit is "landing in the face of the enemy; opposed landing squad in kota bharu was passionately counterattacked ..." but if they meet an enemy it's already clear the landing is opposed, unlike singora}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.30,0:09:21.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Nevertheless, this formation also managed to honor the "Charge" order
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.87,0:09:24.54,Default,,0,0,0,,and broke through the enemy by dint of melee attack. {lit is "closing in on (the enemy, first place, etc.); coming close to; pressing hard attack" so I think they meant "bayonet charge and close quarters combat"}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.03,0:09:28.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Moreover, on December 10th, \Nthe Japanese naval bombers' attack {/attacking planes}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.05,0:09:30.98,Sign,,0,0,0,,British East Indies Fleet sunk off the coast of Malaya {マレー沖にて英国東洋艦隊} {the exact translation would be "far Eastern fleet" but wiki has it https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Indies_Fleet so I'm sticking to this here on}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.31,0:09:33.63,Default,,0,0,0,,sunk two major ships of the British East Indies Fleet: \NPrince of Wales and Repulse.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.98,0:09:35.03,Sign,,0,0,0,,The efficiency of the lightning-fast torpedo {雷撃必殺の魚雷投下}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.63,0:09:36.03,Default,,0,0,0,,With aerial and naval supremacy over their targets, {/over the region obtained}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.03,0:09:39.03,Sign,,0,0,0,,Proved the Japanese planes' flawlessness! {さすが日本機よくぞ擊沈！- as expected of ..., they sink well}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:36.03,0:09:39.26,Default,,0,0,0,,the {Japanese }high command{/army} \Nwas now even more in favor of securing Malaya. {/capturing malay strategy}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.12,0:09:48.14,Default,,0,0,0,,On December 11th, three days after \Nthe Japanese landing on the Malay Peninsula,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.14,0:09:50.29,Default,,0,0,0,,the 8th Australian Division Commander
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.29,0:09:54.76,Default,,0,0,0,,visited the global commander \Nof Britain's East Indies forces, Lieutenant General Percival.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.43,0:10:05.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, I beg your pardon, but the actual war began.\NWars are not won through formalities. {/documents/bureaucracy}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.31,0:10:11.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Our forces are obviously too scattered.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.52,0:10:15.57,Default,,0,0,0,,If we don't {concentrate our troops and }consolidate the front line immediately, \Nwe'll be at great risk!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.34,0:10:22.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Division Commander, with respect, aren't you \Nfretting about the Japanese army more than necessary?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.60,0:10:25.41,Default,,0,0,0,,But sir, the jewels of Singapore's defense,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.41,0:10:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the flagships of the East Indies Fleet, \NPrince of Wales and Repulse were sunk!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.00,0:10:35.12,Default,,0,0,0,,It's true that the Japanese army has airplanes, \Nwhereas we don't. Same goes for tanks.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.12,0:10:40.30,Default,,0,0,0,,But Division Commander, the Malay Peninsula \Ncan only be crossed from north-to-south via two narrow roads. {main road; main thoroughfare; arterial road}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.30,0:10:44.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Moreover, many fortifications are in place \Nalong the border, starting with the Jitra Line.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.98,0:10:51.35,Default,,0,0,0,,It will take the Japanese army at least six months \Nto reach Johor Bahru.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.11,0:10:55.73,Default,,0,0,0,,By then, Singapore would teem \Nwith reinforcements from Britain.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.94,0:11:01.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Such a degree of concern is unwarranted. \NDon't you think so, Division Commander? {/don't have to worry so much}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.11,0:11:05.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh no, I'm still worried, sir.\NThe Japanese are as determined as wolves! {have wolf's fighting spirit; (will to) fight}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.24,0:11:08.20,Default,,0,0,0,,As wolves, you say?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.69,0:11:14.67,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the Jitra Line is also a robust{/solid; strong; firm} position.\NI expect them to hold off the enemy for 3 months at least. {to hold out (e.g. against an attack); to hang on; to withstand; to endure; to last}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.16,0:11:23.55,Default,,0,0,0,,However, this very day, the tank Corps of the 5th Division\Nof the Japanese Army stormed into the Jitra Line.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.18,0:11:27.22,Default,,0,0,0,,The British Far East Commander had erred in his reckoning.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.85,0:11:31.52,Default,,0,0,0,,In contrast to the Japanese Commander, this Commander
Dialogue: 0,0:11:31.52,0:11:35.72,Default,,0,0,0,,was more preoccupied \Nwith paperwork than the actual conflict. {administrative affairs }
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.72,0:12:07.75,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy's here!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.44,0:12:16.02,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army advanced at a tremendous pace.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.02,0:12:19.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Sagging under the charge, \Nthe British troops couldn't counterattack. {unsure he means this, lit is "counterattack in no time"}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.08,0:12:40.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, the element relied upon by the commander of Britain's East Indies,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.17,0:12:45.39,Default,,0,0,0,,the border encompassing Jitra Line, \Nwas completely cut through under a day. {/breached}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.50,0:12:56.56,Default,,0,0,0,,First, tanks rushed in. The trucks were falling into step behind.{/following}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:56.56,0:13:00.07,Default,,0,0,0,,To finish, the Mobile Infantry, \N"Silver Ring", followed on bicycles. {銀輪 is  bicycle wheel; bicycle but lit is "silver ring/wheel/hoop" - it was colloquial name for japanese bicycle infantry in Japanese newspapers of the time, but this name is apparently completely obscured in the west so I wonder if we should preserve it or just go with "bicycle infantry"}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.07,0:13:03.57,Default,,0,0,0,,This tactic was carried on \Neven after Jitra line's dismantlement. {lit: this tactics of sweeping away the jutra line was continued afterwards  -- @Perevodildo  the line you may replace it with: "Using this tactics, which proved effective for dismantling the Jitra Line,"}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.57,0:13:06.84,Default,,0,0,0,,25th Army was thrusting its way \Nthrough the Malay Peninsula. {/charged/rushed into}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.45,0:13:13.93,Default,,0,0,0,,On December 28th already, the 5th Division's charge \Nstaved the British defenders in of Kampar as well,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.93,0:13:16.40,Default,,0,0,0,,only grinding to a halt at the Sungai river.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:16.79,0:13:20.61,Default,,0,0,0,,They had to, as the bridge over it \Nwas detonated by retreating British troops.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.19,0:13:26.84,Default,,0,0,0,,They boldly foisted this on us. {idk what he meant by "we can't help being done so showy; loud; flashy; gaudy"; HA had it "if they did it so quickly" which is probably right and I'm hearing the wrong word}\NLet's sit this out and wait for the engineering battalion.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.84,0:13:27.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Got it!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.89,0:13:40.44,Default,,0,0,0,,On the night of January 4th, the Independent Engineering Regiment had arrived to rebuild the blown bridge. {construction; establishment}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.94,0:13:48.61,Default,,0,0,0,,The Independent Engineering Regiment arrived on the spot. \NPlease accept our apology for the delay. {/we're sorry for being late}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:49.12,0:13:52.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Good to know.{/good job/thanks for hard work} Feel free \Nto enjoy relief at our camp tonight.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.74,0:13:57.12,Default,,0,0,0,,No. We appreciate your hospitality, \Nbut our Blitzkrieg cannot suffer any delay. {lit: I think I should thank you for your kindness; goodwill; kind offer, but the lighting-fast operation is not supposed to have a rest/break/interruption}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.87,0:14:01.79,Default,,0,0,0,,We've no time to sleep. \NPlease let us start the reconstruction work at once. {lit: i want to start work; operation; task}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:02.46,0:14:04.13,Default,,0,0,0,,I see. Permission granted.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.92,0:14:05.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Roger!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.34,0:14:21.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Through conventional warfare, we won't capture it \Neven after half a year! Speed is the key.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:21.73,0:14:24.54,Default,,0,0,0,,As soon as we land, we overrun them, \Nwithout half-measure.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.54,0:14:27.26,Default,,0,0,0,,The forward units \Nhave to cut through the enemy's lines!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.42,0:14:44.81,Default,,0,0,0,,By dint of hard, strenuous labor, under just 2 days, \Nthe construction battalion had completed their job. {/tear-jerkingly/touching; moving; painful, with engineering regiment's hard work, the work; operation; task was over in 2 days}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.81,0:14:55.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.16,0:14:56.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah! Good job! {guess}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:56.68,0:14:57.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Keep it up!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.97,0:15:07.84,Default,,0,0,0,,This enemy stronghold, a sentry to Slim River, \Nis 350km from the capital, {"surimu ni itaru" has to be "opening a way/leading to the slim [river]" but why won't he say river - idk (by the way, the river's name is sungai slim, "slim river" is a name of a settlement); what's "350kilo" idk either, sounds like he just uses it as a kind of proper name - 350kilo base, I would assume he means "350 km from signapore" although that would not be entirely correct either (https://www.mapdevelopers.com/draw-circle-tool.php?circles=%5B%5B350000%2C3.8270354%2C101.4094638%2C%22%23AAAAAA%22%2C%22%23000000%22%2C0.4%5D%5D); btw he's now talking about trolak, the village north of slim river}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.84,0:15:10.66,Default,,0,0,0,,it is the most impregnable position in Malay Peninsula. {precipitous; rugged; inaccessible; impregnable; steep ­- no clue what he's saying about, the position doesn't appear to be mountaneous, so it's not steep, it wasn't a prepared or boasted defensive position either, so why'd he say it's "malaya's #1 kewashi basho" - idk}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:11.20,0:15:16.32,Default,,0,0,0,,The success or failure of the entire blitzkrieg \Ncampaign hinges solely on our ability to capture it.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.83,0:15:21.24,Default,,0,0,0,,It we take our time with it, \Nthe perspective of capturing Singapore is jeopardized. {/it may directly affect the capture of ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:21.64,0:15:26.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Tomorrow, the 7th, our regiment will commence the attack. \NThe planned time is at dawn. {HA had it "regiment will launch an attack tomorrow at dawn on the seventh." and I'm compelled to agree even if idk why'd he say 明７日 as myonanoka; also unsure what's kishite here: to fix (a time, date, etc.); to set/to resolve (to do); to decide upon; to prepare for; to promise; to pledge/to expect; to hope for; to look forward to; to foresee; to anticipate}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.92,0:15:30.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Tank corps, I would ask you to spearhead the attack \Nthrough brute force. That's all. {unsure what he means, lit: I want tank corps to cooperate with the frontal attack - kyoroku may be something else, ryoku is strength/power}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.26,0:15:36.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Commanding officer, sir. I believe, there is a way \Nfor us to level the enemy stronghold easily. {/as for rushing ..., I have an opinion} {Shimada came up with the plan, unusual in World War II, of a night attack using tanks to spearhead the infantry, a dangerous proposition for tanks considering the extremely low visibility factor which would hamper their crews.[3][4]}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.97,0:15:38.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Would you mind hearing me out?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.56,0:15:40.17,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:40.85,0:15:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't think a night's wait would make our tanks helpful. {lit: from a tank's point of view, ... - no clue what's assuimsu, maybe be "easily; readily; quickly" maybe HA's ver something like "asu sugimasu"}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.76,0:15:46.14,Default,,0,0,0,,But an assault tonight would unhorse the enemy{ more efficiently}. {assault; violent attack}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.14,0:15:50.57,Default,,0,0,0,,I believe, however, that for a global attack, \Nour infantry on legs would need to wait for dawn. {I hope he means this, as obviously he cannot go to a tank battle completely without infantry backing even at night}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.21,0:15:53.49,Default,,0,0,0,,What? Are you implying a night attack with tanks?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.82,0:15:59.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. From my analysis of the enemy state,\Na night attack appears to be the best course of action. {/supreme strategy}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:59.77,0:16:04.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Also, at night a tank \Nwould completely conceal it to the most watchful surveillance.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.13,0:16:06.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Besides, such tactic is completely unheard of. {/I've never heard of anyone ... }
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.61,0:16:11.12,Default,,0,0,0,,For these reasons, \Nwe get an excellent opportunity to catch the enemy by surprise. {hope he means this}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:12.80,0:16:14.01,Default,,0,0,0,,I see.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.72,0:16:16.12,Default,,0,0,0,,All right. Let's give it a shot.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:16.12,0:16:17.06,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.34,0:16:23.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Succeed or die trying. {/I wish you luck}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.65,0:16:35.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Late in January 6th, after the sunset, \Na dedicated force of 15 tanks
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.73,0:16:41.78,Default,,0,0,0,,and 100 personnel in leg infantry and engineering battalions \Ndrove straight into the British encampment. {rushing into; breaking into; storming} {straight; as the crow flies}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.59,0:16:57.69,Default,,0,0,0,,All right. Those fires in the woods \Nmust be where the enemy camp is. {guess, no clue what's gonbayashi no nagai, must be "*** hayashi no naka ni" like in HA's ver, but I don't get it - what does it mean "the enemy must be in the forest", where did this come from how'd he conclude it}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.64,0:16:59.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Full alert! {guess, believing HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.57,0:17:17.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Gun position at one o'clock. {sight (e.g. of a gun); aim; alignment} \NLock those woods down at once! {this gonbaya again, would say screw it and assume "kono hayashi chu"} {no clue what's nihaku either, zen'nin is "all members; all hands; everyone; everybody; whole crew" so gotta be something about "coordinated attack"; not in HA's script; haku may be "to sweep; to brush; to clean"}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:22.56,0:17:23.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Fire!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:45.35,0:17:47.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Over there are the enemy's big guns. {/artillery} {historically, thanks to the night attack, the 11th indian division artillery was not in position, therefore they could not mount any resistance to tanks IIRC}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.09,0:17:48.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Close the distance! {believeing HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.70,0:18:07.25,Default,,0,0,0,,All right! Rush straight into the enemy camp! {to step into (e.g. someone else's territory); to break into; to raid} \NClose combat mode! {guess, not in HA's ver, absolutely no clue what he said but we see all the tanks turn around their turrets, now looking forward with their machine guns so apparently it was some command to switch to accurate/anti-infantry weapon instead of cannons due to risk of damaging their own forces with cannons}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.25,0:19:41.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Already weary from retreating, the British would also \Nregret not taking the situation seriously enough. {no clue what's first word, I don't suppose it's winter, lit is "while being tired by fuyu"}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.63,0:19:45.35,Default,,0,0,0,,The rift between them and the Japanese, \Nwho succeeded in executing the Blitzkrieg{ strategy}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:45.35,0:19:48.81,Default,,0,0,0,,was made explicitly clear \Non the battlefields over the last few days. {lit: It clearly separated the light and dark of the battle}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.29,0:19:52.66,Default,,0,0,0,,A report had arrived.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:53.36,0:19:58.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, Kuala Lumpur finally surrendered on January 11th.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:58.01,0:20:02.03,Default,,0,0,0,,I see. So we're currently going a week ahead of schedule.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:02.78,0:20:07.70,Default,,0,0,0,,After our tanks overran their positions on the Slim River, \Nthe enemy morale was at its historical low. {lit: after our tanks took away slim stronghold, the enemy lost his fighting spirit}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.70,0:20:10.91,Default,,0,0,0,,However, it's not yet time \Nto let our guard down. Continue the Blitz! {to relax one's efforts; to let up; to let one's guard down}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.91,0:20:11.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Yessir!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:12.36,0:20:16.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Now then, would it be the 5th Division \Nto cross the finish line first, or the Imperial Guard division? {ichibannori is first (person) to arrive/first rider in a charge and it'll be used again at 21:49}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:16.49,0:20:18.03,Default,,0,0,0,,I look forward finding it out. {lit: tell/convey/let them know I hope/am waiting/anticipate}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.71,0:20:21.84,Default,,0,0,0,,The Javanese army advances,\Nthe British army retreats.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.84,0:20:24.76,Default,,0,0,0,,The fighting in Malaya had become more or less one-sided.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:24.76,0:20:27.24,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the commander-in-chief of the British forces...
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.64,0:20:31.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, the Japanese army \Nis approaching {us here in }Singapore at an alarming rate.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.60,0:20:33.83,Default,,0,0,0,,The wartime regime has to be instated ASAP. {lit: we've no choice but to to change the object of one's interest or focus to wartime regime; war footing}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.83,0:20:38.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Excuse me, division leader,\Nbut my opinion on this differs from yours.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.83,0:20:44.06,Default,,0,0,0,,But sir... Look at it yourself, sir: \NEven Kuala Lumpur had surrendered on the 11th!{/already}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.57,0:20:47.03,Default,,0,0,0,,You shouldn't give way to panic, Division Commander. {to become confused (disconcerted, disorganized, disorganised); to be flustered; to panic}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.83,0:20:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It is of the utmost importance for an officer{/commander}\Nhave his troops and himself stay calm. {actually "prevent disturbance; unrest; agitation; excitement; commotion; turmoil; discomposure; feeling shaken in morale among officers and men" but I think by officers he means this division commander himself so that'd require "including yourself" in english which is too CPS heavy}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.00,0:20:57.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, why not gather the available Malayan ground troops in Singapore to drive the Japanese out decisively? {to rebound; to recoil; to spring back up; to bounce back}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:57.00,0:20:57.86,Default,,0,0,0,,No.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:58.50,0:21:02.52,Default,,0,0,0,,The islands of Singapore don't have \Nnearly enough barracks to accommodate our entire army.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.97,0:21:06.84,Default,,0,0,0,,That's the last you will hear from me{I think he means "I will not try to plead with you any more than that"}.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:06.84,0:21:11.31,Default,,0,0,0,,I will make a last ditch effort \Nof halting the Japanese advance at Johor Bahru. {/I'll definitely try to check; to hold back; to keep at bay; to stop; to prevent; to stem; to curb; to halt ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.38,0:21:47.84,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army was on a winning spree{lit: rode the waves of victory} \Nand marched straight to Singapore, practically unopposed.{at full speed; (at) full tilt; headlong; impetuously; precipitately}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:49.10,0:21:54.60,Default,,0,0,0,,And{ for the moment,} just as the Commander-in-Chief anticipated it, \Nthe competition{/rivalry} for crossing the finish line first had started. {ichibannori again, remember?}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.73,0:22:06.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, it is reported that the Imperial Guard Division \Nis one step ahead of us on the way to Skudai.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:07.57,0:22:10.35,Default,,0,0,0,,What? Our 5th division \Nmust be the first to arrive!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:11.66,0:22:15.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. However, the Imperial Guard division \Nwill only overtake us by a small margin.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.87,0:22:18.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, like hell we let them do that!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:22.29,0:22:22.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.45,0:22:25.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Come on, off we go!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:26.72,0:22:27.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Roger!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:34.56,0:22:36.98,Default,,0,0,0,,These 5th Division guys are in for a surprise!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.98,0:22:39.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, they stand no chance \Nof crossing the finish line first{, the Imperial Guards Division}.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.24,0:22:53.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Which unit do you guys belong to?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.98,0:22:57.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, Imperial Guard Division. \NForward reconnaissance unit. {no clue what's this shoko sekko, sekkou may be "scout; patrol; spy" so I'd assume it's something like "we're scout division"}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:57.04,0:22:59.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, that's interesting.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:00.92,0:23:03.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Our 5th Division had passed through here a long time ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:05.42,0:23:08.62,Default,,0,0,0,,I am the 21st Brigade Commander of 5th Division. {I couldn't find any photo or proof to these events, but supposedly it's 原田憲義 }
Dialogue: 0,0:23:09.09,0:23:10.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Good job anyway.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.19,0:23:13.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Eh, so we're too late, after all?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:18.63,0:23:21.77,Default,,0,0,0,,The heroic defense of the Singapore's lifeline, Johor Bahru
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.77,0:23:25.69,Default,,0,0,0,,by the 8th Australian Division also proved vain, \Nand the city soon fell.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.78,0:23:29.89,Default,,0,0,0,,What exactly is this thing they call war? {no clue what he means, lit: this thing called fighting is any kind of; every; whatsoever; whatever​ thing?}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.45,0:23:32.11,Default,,0,0,0,,And then, what are its goals?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:32.49,0:23:34.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, when to take a decisive action? {again, unsure he means this}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.95,0:23:40.27,Default,,0,0,0,,A commander, able to fully grasp this basic principle, {unsure what he means by "theme; topic; subject matter; motif; project; slogan" and considering replacing this "theme" with something like "tenet" because in english this word makes no sense here}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.89,0:23:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,or a commander, entirely ignorant of it - {/who neglects it}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.06,0:23:48.92,Default,,0,0,0,,is the most precise indicator \Ntelling a winner from a loser,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.88,0:23:56.30,Default,,0,0,0,,as we have witnessed just now \Nfrom the outcome {and moral }of this campaign. {lit: we here are able to see the natural result and lesson of this}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.87,0:24:07.48,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,0)}The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.\NBut also instilled numerous lessons on how to live.{太平洋戦争はわれわれに平和の尊さを教えたがまた生きるための教訓を数多くのこしている}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.05,0:24:12.74,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese land forces' Blitzkrieg through Malaya is over. {/lightning-like rush}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.74,0:24:15.43,Default,,0,0,0,,The new battle for Singapore now begins.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:15.89,0:24:17.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Notwithstanding their seclusion,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:17.95,0:24:22.29,Default,,0,0,0,,the British had decided to hold onto \Ntheir Fortress of Singapore until the bitter end.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:22.79,0:24:26.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Their opponents - the Japanese were forced \Ninto a bloody and brutal battle.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:27.65,0:24:31.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Like the Southern Cross star, \Nattack and defense intersect, in a gamble for one side's survival. {no clue what's this star bullshit but it can't be anything else but 南十字の星の下 - I can't find any relation to malaya or singapore and it's not used by japanese in any second meaning apparently so I'd assume the southern cross is located the same way from japan as singapore or something} {life or death struggle; mortal combat; struggle to the death}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.84,0:24:35.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Please take part in the next decision: \NThe Fall of Singapore. {シンガポール攻略}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.84,0:24:38.31,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(0,400)} Episode 5 \NThe Fall of Singapore {シンガポール攻略}
Comment: 0,0:24:43.11,0:24:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.80,0:24:48.21,Default,,0,0,50,,If you're a man, let's put your strength to test{男だったら　力を試せ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.21,0:24:52.55,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, keep your hopes sizzling{男だったら　希望(のぞみ)を燃やせ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.55,0:24:56.91,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, don't lose your heart{男だったら　くじけるな}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:56.91,0:25:05.48,Default,,0,0,50,,Because there's just you and me, a man and a man{俺もおまえも　男と男}
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.48,0:25:13.71,Default,,0,0,50,,With crimson blood flowing in our veins all the same{おなじ真赤な　血が通う}
